preprocessors.description:
preprocessors
Preprocess this object in-memory when it's loaded, run scripts using the variable 'object' and modify properties about this object before it's used.
File extension: .proc.kts

List<Script>
* At least one entry must be defined, or just remove this list.
Must be a valid Script (use ctrl+space for auto complete!)
preprocessors.x-intellij-html-description:
preprocessors
Preprocess this object in-memory when it's loaded, run scripts using the variable 'object' and modify properties about this object before it's used. File extension: .proc.kts

List

datapackStructures.description:
datapackStructures
The datapack structures. Randomply chooses a structure to place
Ignores every other setting

Must be a valid Structure Key (use ctrl+space for auto complete!)

pieces.description:
pieces
The starting pieces. Randomly chooses a starting piece, then connects pieces using the pools define in the starting piece.

* At least one entry must be defined, or just remove this list.
Must be a valid Jigsaw Piece (use ctrl+space for auto complete!)

maxDepth.description:
maxDepth
The maximum pieces that can step out from the center piece

Integer
* Default Value is 9
* Minimum allowed is 1
* Maximum allowed is 32
maxDepth.x-intellij-html-description:
maxDepth
The maximum pieces that can step out from the center piece

Integer
* Default Value is 9
* Minimum allowed is 1
* Maximum allowed is 32

useMaxPieceSizeForParallaxRadius.description:
useMaxPieceSizeForParallaxRadius
Jigsaw grows the parallax layer which slows iris down a bit. Since there are so many pieces, Iris takes the avg piece size and calculates the parallax radius from that. Unless your structures are using only the biggest pieces, your structure should fit in the chosen size fine. If you are seeing cut-off parts of your structures or broken terrain, turn this option on. This option will pick the biggest piece dimensions and multiply it by your (maxDepth+1) * 2 as the size to grow the parallax layer by. But typically keep this off.

Boolean
* Default Value is false
useMaxPieceSizeForParallaxRadius.x-intellij-html-description:
useMaxPieceSizeForParallaxRadius
Jigsaw grows the parallax layer which slows iris down a bit. Since there are so many pieces, Iris takes the avg piece size and calculates the parallax radius from that. Unless your structures are using only the biggest pieces, your structure should fit in the chosen size fine. If you are seeing cut-off parts of your structures or broken terrain, turn this option on. This option will pick the biggest piece dimensions and multiply it by your (maxDepth+1) * 2 as the size to grow the parallax layer by. But typically keep this off.

Boolean
* Default Value is false

terminate.description:
terminate
If set to true, iris will look for any pieces with only one connector in valid pools for edge connectors and attach them to 'terminate' the paths/piece connectors. Essentially it caps off ends. For example in a village, Iris would add houses to the ends of roads where possible. For terminators to be selected, they can only have one connector or they wont be chosen.

Boolean
* Default Value is true

oneOf.description: Starcast is Iris's own creation. It uses raytrace checks to find a horizontal boundary nearby. 3 Checks in a circle. Typically starcast is used with another interpolation method. See BILINEAR_STARCAST_9 For example. Starcast is meant to 'break up' large, abrupt cliffs to make cheap interpolation smoother.

interpolationMethod.description:
interpolationMethod
The interpolation method if the coordinateScale is greater than 1. This blends the image into noise. For nearest neighbor, use NONE.

InterpolationMethod
An interpolation method (or function) is simply a method of smoothing a position based on surrounding points on a grid. Bicubic for example is smoother, but has 4 times the checks than Bilinear for example. Try using BILINEAR_STARCAST_9 for beautiful results.
    
* Default Value is BILINEAR_STARCAST_6
Must be a valid InterpolationMethod (use ctrl+space for auto complete!)
